    "header": "Day 3: Password Security and Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)",
    "body": "Strong passwords are the first defense against unauthorized access. Unfortunately, many breaches occur because employees reuse or create weak passwords. A secure password should contain a mix of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols, with at least twelve characters. Avoid using personal information like birthdays or pet names. Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) adds a critical second layer by requiring additional verification—such as a text message, authentication app, or fingerprint scan—making it far harder for attackers to gain access even if passwords are stolen. Password managers can help generate and store complex passwords securely. Consistently applying strong password practices protects not only your personal accounts but also the company’s digital assets, cloud platforms, and internal systems.",
    "best_practices": "Create strong, unique passwords for every system, enable MFA on all accounts, and change passwords immediately if you suspect any compromise."
